<font color="#FF0000">SOME GENERAL THOUGHTS....</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec 20 18:12:11 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I wish to thank all of you who have responded to this dialog &quot;string,&quot; and a special notice to all of you who have &quot;dropped-in&quot; and have read the exchanges, but as of yet, have not left your comments, your views will be highly valued.<br><br>
All of you who have responded have much to offer my students. I am fortunate to have 30 hours, Mike (above) gets to present information on Vietnam to his class of university students for only one hour! Hats off to Mike: I wouldn't know where to begin.<br><br>
A colleague of mine at UC Davis, Eric Schroeder, published a book in 1992 entitled: Vietnam, We've All Been There (Praeger). Whether or not we were veterans or civilians during the Vietnam War era... in one way or another &quot;we've all been there.&quot;<br><br>
I cannot speak about Vietnam from the perspective of a veteran, but I can speak about Vietnam from the perspective of having visited three times during the past four years. How does one explain Vietnam to others? Your point, Randall (above), is clear, as is Arthur's response (above). &quot;History&quot; is told through the prism of the instructor.<br><br>
On my first visit to Hanoi in 1993, old women walking with their grandchildren would approach me and say, &quot;American?&quot; And when I would say yes, they would continue, &quot;You are welcome here.&quot; And the grandchildren would smile shyly from behind grandmother's skirt. Some of these women over the course of the war went down the &quot;trail.&quot; One of the most prominent Vietnamese scientists today, the ecologist Vo Quy, told me two years ago: &quot;It was tough on the trail. I went back and forth from north to south three times. It was tough.&quot; He would smile, then laugh, and we would talk further about ecology. <br><br>
In 1993 I drove the length of Vietnam with Vietnamese colleagues looking at agriculture, seeking opportunities for my university and theirs to collaborate on topics of mutual interest. You learn a considerable amount about people when you drive 1200 miles, sometimes at 5 mph over roads being repaired by hand, not by machine; eating and drinking 3-3-3 beer at roadside stands; lighting jos at specific shrines just before the descent down winding roads with switch-backs too numerous to count, and then laughing together with the driver, when we all reached &quot;level ground&quot; safely. <br><br>
I saw a beautiful land, marked by war and post-war ecological problems: silted rivers, malaria pools, where once the river had flowed directly to the South China Sea. Damaged bridges, buildings, bomb craters, churned earth; along one 150 mile stretch near the sea, I never saw a bird. <br><br>
And every 5-10 kilometer there would be a cemetery, and another, and another. The urgency and passon of politics -- the ancient human foe -- passes with time. The passing, however, does not end the pain experienced by families who lost sons and daughters, husbands and wives, parents and grandparents to political-military conflict. This is the pain experienced by both Americans and by Vietnamese.<br><br>
I tell my students: forgive but remember... remember why all this happined. I tell my students my generation was the generation of the Vietnam War; it also can be the generation of peace. <br><br>
In 1955 I witnessed an atom bomb test; the eerie light from that early morning explosion lit up and filled my parent's bedroom miliseconds after the blast was televised.. and we lived more than 400 miles from Yucca Flats. My generation lived through the Cold War, the fear of Sputnik -- that the Reds had their thing in space, so why study for examinations? The Berlin Wall and all that...<br><br>
But the Wall came down; Arafat and Rabin shook hands on the White House lawn; the fall of Communism in eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union; America and Vietnam established diplomatic relations.  A world turned upside down, one of enormous opportunity, excitement, and promise, for the current generation. A time, too, to get beyond the war into the 21st century. <br><br>
In Vietnam the war is over. It is unsettling to see and experience this basic fact: Vietnam was a country nearly destroyed by war... but today, Americans are invited back. Yes, because of $$$$, but also because of something else. America is admired by many millions of Vietnamese today because of its Constitution, because of the promise of America. With Doi Moi and economic &quot;restructuring&quot; the Government of Vietnam is &quot;riding the back of a tiger.&quot; How can a Communist government allow private enterprise (which they do); e-mail and access to web sites (which they do); and still expect to maintain a Marxist-Leninism approach to managing their economy and people? In use today in Vietnam is a common phrase: &quot;Communistic-Capitalism.&quot; Now what does that mean? How would you ever explain this mixture of &quot;isms&quot; to the men and women who fought fiercly and died for their homeland, for &quot;democracy,&quot; for their country? <br><br>
That is what haunts me. <br><br>
America lingers over Vietnam, and we as a people remain haunted. <br><br>
Randall, perhaps you are right; will people know about Khe Sanh, Hue, Da Nang, Camp Caroll, the Rockpile, A-Shau Valley 50 or 100 years from now? I don't know but I would hope so. I do remember the names of places from the American Revolutionary War, certainly the places of battle in the eastern Mediterranean where I have worked for the past 20 years. Will teaching this class on Vietnam change things? Things can't be changed, but participants can be exposed to the who, what, where, when, why, and how from a variety of perspectives -- and from this exposure, they may just learn how to avoid other &quot;Vietnams&quot; in the future.<br><br>
The course is taking shape (content, organization, structure). We are on a quarter system which means 10 weeks.. a sprint. That means 10 class meetings of 3 hours each. Students are advised that they should consider 15 hours/week as the time required for in-class activities and individual and team activities during the week.<br><br>
The first meeting (hour 1) will be basic introductions, class requirements, followed by an introduction to the people, land, and pre-history of Vietnam with assigned readings. First meeting (hour 2) will be slides that consider a range of images associated with the geography and people of Vietnam, from the 19th century through 1996. Students don't usually associate stands of pine tree forests or deserts with Vietnam (the country has both). Most preconceived images have been learned from Hollywood. The final hour will be spent reviewing individual and team assignments for the next week. Participants will have 30-50 pages to read each week (a portion of this reading has been &quot;logged-down&quot; from the POV web-site). Participants will keep an electronic journal (2 entries per week) that will be e-mailed directly to me. Participants also will be conducting interviews during the quarter among the following groups in central California: Vietnam veterans who saw combat (both for and against the war); Vietnam veterans who were not in combat; nurses and medical care personnel who served in Vietnam; Vietnamese-American veterans; Vietnamese-American civilians (from the Saigon evacuation and later Boat-People); American civilans who were for the war, but didn't serve; and American civilians who were against the war and were active in the Peace Movement. <br><br>
Pannelists throughout the quarter will include perspectives from:<br><br>
1.Geographers, Historians, Military Intelligence Officers on how America became involved in Vietnam;<br><br>
2.American and Vietnamese who will address the planning, management, and conduct of the war;<br><br>
3.American veterans who will address issues relating to: life and activities during combat<br><br>
4.Families of American combat veterans who will address issues associated with: Agent Orange, PTSD, coming-home adjustment, and POW/MIA issues;<br><br>
5.Vietnamese-Americans, members of the diaspora, who will address issues associated with: political events in South Vietnam during the last days before the fall of Saigon (or you wish, the unification of the country), the decision to come to America, risking one's life for freedom, adjustment in a new land, and perspectives on Vietnam today;<br><br>
6.American scientists and business leaders who have visited Vietnam during the past five years, who will address issues associated with: Vietnam... 1997.... the realities and the promise.<br><br>
Throughout the quarter seminar participants also will focus on five of six topics (students will form five teams of four members each) for further, in-depth study. Topics offered are:<br><br>
A.AMERICAN AND VIETNAMESE POPULAR CULTURE AS A REFLECTION OF THE TIMES (1950-1997) WITH EMPHASIS ON THE WAR YEARS,a survey of the art, film, music, and poetry of both Vietnam and the United States;<br><br>
B.ETHICAL CONDUCT WHEN CONDUCTING WAR, a survey of the just war concept, Geneva convention protocols, treatment of prisoners of war, attrocities (both sides), interrogation techniques (both sides), and post-war so-called &quot;re-education camps;&quot;<br><br>
C.The TET OFFENSIVE, a comparative examination of media coverage during World War II and the Vietnam War; consideraton of the Tet offensive from the perspectives of North Vietnam, the Viet Cong, South Vietnam, American troops, and from the U.S. Peace Movement; special attention to events at Hue and in Saigon;<br><br>
D.AFTERMATH: WAR AND NON-WAR-RELATED ECOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL CHANGE, an examination of deforestation, hydrological changes, soil erosion and contamination, salinization in the Meking delta, coastal mangrove destruction, and loss of animal species diversity;<br><br>
E.AFTERMATH: WAR- AND NON-WAR HEALTH AND NUTRITION ISSUES, an examination of malaria and disease spread and unexploded ordnance in Vietnam, veteran health issues in the United States, and malnutrition in both Vietnam and among groups of Vietnam-era Americans;<br><br>
F.VIET NAM, 1997, an examination of the decision to establish diplomtic relations, the unusual blend of Marxism and Capitalism (Doi Moi), press freedom, tourism, and investment opportunities -- from different perspectives: attitudes of Vietnamese veterans (in Vietnam and in the United States), American veterans -- with an exploration of the U.S. veterans restoration and reconciliation projects (education; building clinics; humanitarian efforts).<br><br>
One of the highlights of the class will be &quot;personalizing&quot; the human cost of war when the seminar participants meet with California veterans and Vietnamese-American civilians and veterans at the California Veterans Memorial in Sacramento for an evening of memory and communication.<br><br>
The date and time of this event is: <br><br>
7:00 P.M., February 27th, 1997, at the California Veterans Memorial (rain or shine). <br><br>
On behalf of my students I invite Vietnam and Vietnamese-American veterans, nurses and medical staff, in the central California area to meet and speak with my students the evening of the 27th.<br><br>
Thank you for your consideration.<br><br>

